---
import Callout from "../../components/Callout.astro";
import OnThisPage from "../../components/OnThisPage.astro";
import Step from "../../components/Step.astro";
import TroubleshootItem from "../../components/TroubleshootItem.astro";
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Run your own model · Cloud Speech for Chrome"
  description="Run a self-hosted OpenAI-compatible text-to-speech engine like LocalAI or Speaches and connect it to the Cloud Speech Chrome extension. Free and private."
  root="../../"
  active="local"
>
  <main class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-12">
    <p>
      <a class="link text-sm text-stone-600" href="../../#guides">← Back to all guides</a>
    </p>

    <header class="mt-8">
      <p
        class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full bg-custom/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-stone-700"
      >
        <span class="h-2 w-2 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Setup guide
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Run your own model</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
        A speech engine on your own machine keeps every request local: nothing leaves your
        computer, and there is no per-character charge. The engines below each serve a family of
        open voice models behind one URL, so you aren't tied to a single model. In exchange you
        install and run the engine yourself. It takes about 10 minutes if you're comfortable
        with a terminal.
      </p>
      <OnThisPage
        items={[
          { href: "#steps", label: "Setup steps" },
          { href: "#costs", label: "Costs" },
          { href: "#remove", label: "Remove access" },
          { href: "#cli", label: "CLI setup" },
          { href: "#troubleshooting", label: "Troubleshooting" },
        ]}
      />
    </header>

    <div class="card mt-8 p-5">
      <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold">What you'll need</h2>
      <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
        <li>A computer that can run the engine (some models want a GPU, smaller ones don't)</li>
        <li>A terminal, and Docker or Python depending on the engine</li>
        <li>About 10 minutes</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <ol
      id="steps"
      class="relative mt-12 scroll-mt-24 space-y-12 before:absolute before:top-2 before:bottom-2 before:left-4 before:w-px before:bg-stone-200"
    >
      <Step n={1} title="Pick an engine">
        <p>Any engine that implements OpenAI's speech endpoint works. Common choices:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-5 marker:text-stone-400">
          <li>
            <a class="link" href="https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/text_to_speech">LiteLLM</a>: a
            local proxy that turns one endpoint into many providers; route to ElevenLabs,
            MiniMax, OpenAI, Azure, Polly, or Vertex/Gemini with your own keys
          </li>
          <li>
            <a class="link" href="https://localai.io">LocalAI</a>: a full local OpenAI
            replacement that loads multiple TTS backends, such as Kokoro, Piper, and Coqui
          </li>
          <li>
            <a class="link" href="https://github.com/speaches-ai/speaches">Speaches</a>: a
            lighter server that runs Kokoro and Piper voices behind one endpoint
          </li>
          <li>
            <a class="link" href="https://github.com/remsky/Kokoro-FastAPI">Kokoro-FastAPI</a>:
            the quickest start if the Kokoro model is all you need; one Docker command and it's
            running
          </li>
          <li>openedai-speech: a small server that serves open TTS models on this API</li>
        </ul>
      </Step>

      <Step n={2} title="Start it">
        <p>
          Each engine documents its own install: see the
          <a class="link" href="https://localai.io/basics/getting_started/">LocalAI</a> or
          <a class="link" href="https://speaches.ai">Speaches</a> getting-started pages. Most run
          as a Docker container or a Python package and listen on a local port.
        </p>
        <p>For Kokoro-FastAPI, one Docker command starts a server on port 8880:</p>
        <pre class="cli-block mt-2"><code is:raw>docker run -d --name kokoro -p 8880:8880 ghcr.io/remsky/kokoro-fastapi-cpu</code></pre>
        <p>
          For a LiteLLM proxy, install it (<span class="value">pip install 'litellm[proxy]'</span>)
          and start it with the model you want to route to:
        </p>
        <pre class="cli-block mt-2"><code is:raw>litellm --model openai/tts-1</code></pre>
        <p class="text-stone-500">
          For more than one backend, or for providers that need their own keys, use a LiteLLM
          config file instead of the <span class="value">--model</span> flag; see the
          <a class="link" href="https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/text_to_speech">LiteLLM TTS docs</a>.
        </p>
        <Callout title="Good to know" tone="neutral">
          The URL you'll give the extension ends in <span class="value">/v1</span>: for example
          <span class="value">http://localhost:8880/v1</span> for Kokoro-FastAPI,
          <span class="value">http://localhost:4000/v1</span> for LiteLLM, or your engine's own
          port.
        </Callout>
      </Step>

      <Step n={3} title="Connect the extension">
        <ol class="list-decimal space-y-1.5 pl-5 marker:text-stone-400">
          <li>Click the extension icon in your browser toolbar</li>
          <li>Open <strong>Settings → OpenAI-compatible</strong></li>
          <li>
            Paste the <strong>Server URL</strong>, e.g.
            <span class="value">http://localhost:4000/v1</span> or the engine's port
          </li>
          <li>
            Enter an <strong>API key</strong> only if the server requires one (local servers
            usually don't)
          </li>
          <li>
            Optionally list <strong>voice names</strong> separated by commas, and one or more
            <strong>models</strong>, also separated by commas (the default is
            <span class="value">tts-1</span>, which most servers accept)
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>Save &amp; test</strong></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          The extension first asks the server for its voice list, so you can usually leave the
          voices field empty. If the server doesn't report voices, it falls
          back to OpenAI's nine standard voice names, and anything you type in the field takes
          priority. Each model you list becomes its own row per voice in the voice picker, so
          one server can expose several models at once and you can switch between them per read.
          Once the test passes, highlight text on any page, right-click, and choose
          <em>Read aloud</em>, or press <kbd>Ctrl/Cmd+Shift+S</kbd>.
        </p>
      </Step>
    </ol>

    <!-- Costs -->
    <section class="card mt-12 scroll-mt-24 p-6" id="costs">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold">
        <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Costs
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-700">
        <strong>Free to run</strong> once you have the hardware; there is no per-character charge
        at all, and electricity is the only meter. The engines above are free software. For how
        this compares to the cloud providers, see our
        <a class="link" href="../../pricing/">provider comparison</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Remove access -->
    <section class="card mt-12 scroll-mt-24 p-6" id="remove">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold">
        <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Remove access when you're done
      </h2>
      <ol class="mt-3 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-700">
        <li>Stop the server process (Ctrl+C) or delete its container.</li>
        <li>
          In the extension, open <strong>Settings → OpenAI-compatible</strong> and clear the
          saved fields (or turn the provider off).
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <!-- CLI alternative -->
    <section class="card mt-12 scroll-mt-24 p-6" id="cli">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold">
        <span class="h-2.5 w-2.5 rounded-full bg-custom"></span>
        Prefer the command line?
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-700">
        This guide is already mostly command line. The short version for LiteLLM, routing to a
        backend you hold a key for:
      </p>
      <pre class="cli-block mt-4"><code is:raw>pip install 'litellm[proxy]'
export OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
litellm --model openai/tts-1
# Server URL for the extension: http://localhost:4000/v1</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-700">
        Removal is stopping the process (Ctrl+C) and revoking whatever backend key you exported.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Troubleshooting -->
    <section class="mt-12 scroll-mt-24" id="troubleshooting">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Troubleshooting</h2>
      <div class="card mt-4 divide-y divide-stone-100">
        <TroubleshootItem title="Connection refused or network errors">
          <p>
            The server isn't reachable at the URL you saved. Check that it's actually running,
            that the port in the URL matches the one the server listens on, and that the URL
            ends in
            <span class="value">/v1</span>. Then click <strong>Save &amp; test</strong> again.
          </p>
        </TroubleshootItem>
        <TroubleshootItem title="401 or unauthorized errors">
          <p>
            The server requires an API key. Paste it into the extension's API key field; for a
            LiteLLM proxy with authentication enabled this is the proxy's master or virtual key,
            not the backend provider's key.
          </p>
        </TroubleshootItem>
        <TroubleshootItem title="No voices, or the wrong voices, in the picker">
          <p>
            The extension asks the server for its voice list first and falls back to OpenAI's
            standard names if that fails. If your server's voices don't show up, type their names
            into the <strong>Voices</strong> field yourself, separated by commas, and save again.
          </p>
        </TroubleshootItem>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-600">
        For no audio, missing voices, or keyboard shortcut problems, see the
        <a class="link" href="../../troubleshooting/">troubleshooting guide</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p class="mt-10 text-sm leading-relaxed text-stone-600">
      Rather skip the setup? A hosted service works with the same extension settings; see
      <a class="link" href="../custom/">OpenAI-compatible</a>. Or pick a cloud provider:
      <a class="link" href="../polly/">Amazon Polly</a>,
      <a class="link" href="../azure/">Azure Speech</a>,
      <a class="link" href="../google/">Google Cloud TTS</a>, or
      <a class="link" href="../openai/">OpenAI</a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>
